2:33 PM/ Room 301. Defendant Cesar O Fernandez-Reyes appeared by video, in custody at the Langlade County Jail.  Attorney Robert Thomas Ruth in court for Cesar O Fernandez-Reyes.  Attorney Kelly L Hays in court for State of Wisconsin. All appearances are by Zoom. Interpreter Susan Rascon appears by Zoom, sworn in as interpreter. Court reviews reason for today's hearing; counsel has agreed to some discovery issues and others need to be decided by Court.  State recites issues that are agreed upon. 1-Copy of video recording of victim and witness with DOBs as stated on record shall remain available to presiding judge; State will mail defense counsel the DVD. Attny Ruth in agreement. 2- Defense counsel may save the files to laptop and desktop computers. Def. counsel agrees to delete files upon completion of case. No additional copies or any portion of DVD should be made by Def. atty, investigator, expert or any other rep. of defendant without specific order. Attny Ruth in agreement and Def. understands.  3- Copies shall not be used for any purpose other than for defense to prepare or for court to review. 4- All copies of disk shall be contained in sealed folder with protective order on top.  Attny Ruth makes clarification. Court confirms that agreement is that all hard copies of DVD to be kept in sealed folder with protective order on top. Attny Ruth in agreement and Def. understands. State recites issues in dispute:  State is requesting condition that video may only be viewed by specific individuals and that there also be a prohibition in showing the transcript. Anybody who views the video sign an agreement that they have seen the protective order and that they be subject to the Court's contempt. Court confirms the disputed issues. 1. No part of these videos may be viewed by anyone other than the parties, counsel of record, their investigators, their experts and the Court. State indicates that condition should also include transcripts. Attny Ruth cites position as to State's requested conditions. Response by State. Further arguments. Remarks by the Court. The Court indicates the use of lay witnesses may be discovered by the defense without showing the videos or transcripts. If defense determines it is vitally important that individuals see video or transcripts, they may then ask the Court for permission and give reasons why. State is to draft order. Attny Ruth makes further argument. Remarks by the Court. Attny Ruth asks Court if it would consider asking permission from Court under seal not viewable by the State. State objects. The Court confirms ruling, urges parties to continue dialog re: issues and exploring additional possible stipulations. Counsel may supplement the record for possible reconsideration if no stipulation reached.  Court indicates language on last issue should be as follows: No portion of the subject videos that have been discussed today or transcripts of any portions thereof, may be viewed by anyone other than the parties, their counsel, their investigators, their experts, and the Court without further permission from the Court. If such permission is sought, it may be put in writing and be presented to the Court. Court will not accept in camera invitation. If lay witnesses are needed to be shown videos or transcripts, Attny Ruth is to provide identity of witness and reason he needs them to see it. Attny Ruth asks that experts include his typists. State is agreeable. Court will allow typists to be included in order.  Court clarifies final issue: The State wants Court to order anyone who views the videos or part of them or transcripts thereof, must sign an agreement that they are aware of the protective order and terms thereof, and understand that a violation thereof, would subject them to potential contempt sanctions. State in agreement with Court's paraphrase. Attny Ruth gives argument. Response by State. Remarks by the Court. Court orders wording for final issue: Anyone who receives copy of the subject matter videos or any part thereof, or transcript of any part thereof, must sign a document that they are aware of the protective order made by the Court today and the terms thereof, and know that a violation thereof would subject them to potential contempt sanctions. Def. has no questions.  Status conference already set for Dec. 5. Adjourned at 3:39 p.m.
